When Ainsley Earhardt asked Tucker Carlson, â€œWhat happens next though Tucker, going forward? Will we be able to find out any of this information, or will is it something that will just be swept under the rug again?â€ Carlson responded: The President himself can find out. And he can let the rest of us know by declassifying this information. He has theÂ power to do that. He can unilaterally declassify whatever he wants. And I hope that he will.Â Because a lot of people like me, who have lived here you know, my whole life and have watched this stuff happen, are veryÂ suspicious that this kind of thing happens regularly. AndÂ again, that shakes everyoneâ€™s faith in theÂ institution ofÂ government. Itâ€™sÂ terrible. It has a chilling effect in the most basic way. If you think that theÂ government isÂ listening to you, that your political enemies canÂ destroy you, if you step out of line, thenÂ youâ€™reÂ no longer livingÂ in a free society.â€ Â Â Congressional investigators have confirmed that a top FBI official met with Democratic Party lawyers to talk about allegations of Donald Trump-Russia collusion weeks before the 2016 election, and before the bureau secured a search warrant targeting Trumpâ€™s campaign.Former FBI general counsel James Baker met during the 2016 season with at least one attorney from Perkins Coie, the Democratic National Committeeâ€™s private law firm.Thatâ€™s the firm used by the DNC and Hillary Clintonâ€™s campaign to secretly pay research firmÂ Fusion GPS and Christopher Steele, a former British intelligence operative, to compile a dossier of uncorroborated raw intelligence alleging Trump and Moscow were colluding to hijack the presidential election.The dossier, though mostly unverified, was then used by the FBI as the main evidence seeking a Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA) warrant targeting the Trump campaign in the final days of the campaign.The revelation was confirmed both in contemporaneous evidence and testimony secured by a joint investigation by Republicans on the House Judiciary and Government Oversight committees, my source tells me.It means the FBI had good reason to suspect the dossier was connected to the DNCâ€™s main law firm and was the product of a Democratic opposition-research effort to defeat Trump â€” yet failed to disclose that information to the FISA court in October 2016, when the Bureau applied for a FISA warrant to surveil Trump campaign adviser Carter Page.â€œThis is a bombshell that unequivocally shows the real collusion was between the FBI and Donald Trumpâ€™s opposition â€” the DNC, Hillary, and a Trump-hating British intel officer â€” to hijack the election, rather than some conspiracy between Putin and Trump,â€ a knowledgeable source told me.Baker was interviewed by lawmakers behind closed doors on Wednesday. Sources declined to divulge his testimony, other than to say it confirmed other evidence about the contact between the Perkins Coie law firm and the FBI. -John Soloman, Opinion Contributor forÂ The HillOn September 17, 2018, the White House answered calls by several GOP lawmakers to declassify the documents related to the Russian investigation, and announced that President Trump was ordering the declassification of the FISA application used to spy on Carter Page, as well as the declassification of the text messages without redaction, betweenÂ James Comey, Andrew McCabe, Peter Strzok, Lisa Page, and Bruce Ohr.At the request of a number of committees of Congress, and for reasons of transparency, the President has directed the Office of the Director of National Intelligence and the Department of Justice (including the FBI) to provide for the immediate declassification of the following materials: (1) pages 10-12 and 17-34 of the June 2017 application to the FISA court in the matter of Carter W. Page; (2) all FBI reports of interviews with Bruce G. Ohr prepared in connection with the Russia investigation; and (3) all FBI reports of interviews prepared in connection with all Carter Page FISA applications.In addition, President Donald J. Trump has directed the Department of Justice (including the FBI) to publicly release all text messages relating to the Russia investigation, without redaction, of James Comey, Andrew McCabe, Peter Strzok, Lisa Page, and Bruce Ohr.Watch, as MSNBC host Joy Reid and guests mock President Trump for making the ridiculous claim that his campaign was wiretapped. Democrat Eric Swalwell (CA), claims that wiretapping would be something Donald Trump would want to do, as Joy laughs.Trending: KATIE HOPKINS WARNS AMERICANS Of Grave Danger Ahead: â€œDo Not Let This Great Country Become The United Kingdomâ€ [VIDEO]Â Â Â 
